---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="Fertility Medications" description="Guide to fertility medications including Clomid, Letrozole, and gonadotropins. Learn about oral and injectable options, costs, success rates, and side effects.">
	<section class="hero-mini">
		<div class="container">
			<nav class="breadcrumb">
				<a href="/treatments/">Treatments</a> <span>/</span> Medications
			</nav>
			<h1>Fertility Medications</h1>
			<p class="lead">Oral and injectable medications used to induce or enhance ovulation</p>
		</div>
	</section>

	<section class="content-container">
		<div class="intro-box">
			<p>Fertility medications are often the first-line treatment for women with irregular ovulation or unexplained infertility. These medications work by stimulating the ovaries to produce one or more eggs.</p>
		</div>

		<h2>Oral Medications</h2>

		<div class="med-cards">
			<div class="med-card">
				<div class="med-header">
					<span class="med-icon">C</span>
					<div>
						<h3>Clomiphene Citrate</h3>
						<span class="brand-names">Clomid, Serophene</span>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div class="med-body">
					<div class="med-detail">
						<span class="label">How it works</span>
						<p>Blocks estrogen receptors in the brain, causing increased FSH production and ovulation.</p>
					</div>
					<div class="med-detail">
						<span class="label">Protocol</span>
						<p>50-150mg daily for 5 days, starting on cycle day 3-5.</p>
					</div>
					<div class="med-stats">
						<div class="stat">
							<span class="value">80%</span>
							<span class="label">will ovulate</span>
						</div>
						<div class="stat">
							<span class="value">10-12%</span>
							<span class="label">pregnancy/cycle</span>
						</div>
						<div class="stat">
							<span class="value">$10-$100</span>
							<span class="label">per cycle</span>
						</div>
					</div>
					<div class="med-notes">
						<p><strong>Side effects:</strong> Hot flashes, mood changes, headaches, visual disturbances</p>
						<p><strong>Multiple risk:</strong> 5-10% twins, &lt;1% higher-order</p>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>

			<div class="med-card featured">
				<div class="med-badge">First-Line for PCOS</div>
				<div class="med-header">
					<span class="med-icon">L</span>
					<div>
						<h3>Letrozole</h3>
						<span class="brand-names">Femara</span>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div class="med-body">
					<div class="med-detail">
						<span class="label">How it works</span>
						<p>Aromatase inhibitor that lowers estrogen, triggering FSH release.</p>
					</div>
					<div class="med-detail">
						<span class="label">Protocol</span>
						<p>2.5-7.5mg daily for 5 days, starting on cycle day 3-5.</p>
					</div>
					<div class="med-stats">
						<div class="stat">
							<span class="value good">27.5%</span>
							<span class="label">live birth (PCOS)</span>
						</div>
						<div class="stat">
							<span class="value">Fewer</span>
							<span class="label">side effects</span>
						</div>
						<div class="stat">
							<span class="value">$20-$150</span>
							<span class="label">per cycle</span>
						</div>
					</div>
					<div class="med-notes">
						<p><strong>Advantages:</strong> Lower multiple pregnancy rate, better endometrial lining</p>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
		</div>

		<div class="callout-box study">
			<div class="callout-header">
				<span class="callout-icon">S</span>
				<strong>Letrozole vs. Clomid (NEJM Study)</strong>
			</div>
			<p>A landmark multicenter trial of 750 women with PCOS found letrozole resulted in significantly higher live birth rates (<strong>27.5% vs. 19.1%</strong>) compared to clomiphene. Letrozole is now considered first-line treatment for PCOS.</p>
			<a href="https://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMoa1313517" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="source-link">Legro RS, et al. NEJM 2014</a>
		</div>

		<h2>Injectable Medications (Gonadotropins)</h2>

		<div class="med-cards">
			<div class="med-card">
				<div class="med-header">
					<span class="med-icon">F</span>
					<div>
						<h3>FSH Medications</h3>
						<span class="brand-names">Follistim, Gonal-F, Bravelle</span>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div class="med-body">
					<div class="med-detail">
						<span class="label">How it works</span>
						<p>Directly stimulates the ovaries to produce follicles.</p>
					</div>
					<div class="med-detail">
						<span class="label">Protocol</span>
						<p>Daily injections for 8-14 days with monitoring.</p>
					</div>
					<div class="med-stats">
						<div class="stat">
							<span class="value">$1,500-$6,000+</span>
							<span class="label">per cycle</span>
						</div>
					</div>
					<div class="med-notes">
						<p><strong>Requires:</strong> Frequent ultrasound and blood monitoring</p>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>

			<div class="med-card compact">
				<div class="med-header">
					<span class="med-icon">T</span>
					<div>
						<h3>hCG Trigger Shots</h3>
						<span class="brand-names">Ovidrel, Pregnyl, Novarel</span>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div class="med-body">
					<p>Triggers final egg maturation and ovulation. Ovulation occurs 36-40 hours after injection.</p>
					<div class="med-stats inline">
						<div class="stat">
							<span class="value">$50-$200</span>
							<span class="label">per injection</span>
						</div>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>

			<div class="med-card compact">
				<div class="med-header">
					<span class="med-icon">G</span>
					<div>
						<h3>GnRH Agonists & Antagonists</h3>
						<span class="brand-names">Lupron, Ganirelix, Cetrotide</span>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div class="med-body">
					<p>Prevents premature ovulation during IVF cycles. Typically part of IVF protocols, not standalone treatment.</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</div>

		<h2>Medication Protocols</h2>

		<div class="protocol-grid">
			<div class="protocol-card">
				<h3>Timed Intercourse</h3>
				<p>Oral medications + monitoring + timed intercourse at home</p>
				<ul>
					<li>Least invasive approach</li>
					<li>Good first step for unexplained infertility</li>
					<li>Lower cost than IUI or IVF</li>
				</ul>
			</div>
			<div class="protocol-card">
				<h3>Superovulation + IUI</h3>
				<p>Oral or injectable medications + IUI procedure</p>
				<ul>
					<li>Increases number of eggs available</li>
					<li>Combined with IUI for better sperm delivery</li>
					<li>Higher success rates than timed intercourse</li>
				</ul>
			</div>
		</div>

		<h2>Monitoring During Treatment</h2>

		<div class="monitoring-box">
			<p>Most medication cycles require monitoring to:</p>
			<div class="monitoring-grid">
				<div class="monitoring-item">
					<span class="icon">U</span>
					<strong>Track follicle development</strong>
					<span>via transvaginal ultrasound</span>
				</div>
				<div class="monitoring-item">
					<span class="icon">H</span>
					<strong>Measure hormone levels</strong>
					<span>estradiol, LH, progesterone</span>
				</div>
				<div class="monitoring-item">
					<span class="icon">T</span>
					<strong>Time ovulation</strong>
					<span>for intercourse or IUI</span>
				</div>
				<div class="monitoring-item">
					<span class="icon">!</span>
					<strong>Prevent complications</strong>
					<span>like OHSS</span>
				</div>
			</div>
		</div>

		<div class="callout-box warning">
			<div class="callout-header">
				<span class="callout-icon">!</span>
				<strong>Ovarian Hyperstimulation Syndrome (OHSS)</strong>
			</div>
			<p>A potential complication where ovaries become swollen and painful. Mild cases are common; severe cases are rare but require medical attention. Risk is higher with injectable medications.</p>
		</div>

		<h2>Cost Summary</h2>

		<div class="cost-table-wrapper">
			<table class="styled-table">
				<thead>
					<tr>
						<th>Treatment</th>
						<th>Medication</th>
						<th>Monitoring</th>
						<th>Total/Cycle</th>
					</tr>
				</thead>
				<tbody>
					<tr>
						<td>Clomid/Letrozole + timed intercourse</td>
						<td>$10-$150</td>
						<td>$200-$500</td>
						<td><strong>$200-$650</strong></td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td>Clomid/Letrozole + IUI</td>
						<td>$10-$150</td>
						<td>$200-$500</td>
						<td><strong>$500-$1,500</strong></td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td>Injectables + timed intercourse</td>
						<td>$1,500-$5,000</td>
						<td>$500-$1,000</td>
						<td><strong>$2,000-$6,000</strong></td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td>Injectables + IUI</td>
						<td>$1,500-$5,000</td>
						<td>$500-$1,000</td>
						<td><strong>$2,500-$7,000</strong></td>
					</tr>
				</tbody>
			</table>
		</div>

		<h2>When to Move On</h2>

		<div class="next-steps">
			<p>If you haven't conceived after 3-6 cycles of oral medications with or without IUI, your doctor may recommend:</p>
			<div class="next-steps-grid">
				<div class="step">Switching medications</div>
				<div class="step">Adding injectable medications</div>
				<div class="step">Moving to IVF</div>
				<div class="step">Additional testing</div>
			</div>
		</div>

		<div class="nav-footer">
			<a href="/treatments/" class="back-link">← Back to Treatment Options</a>
			<a href="/treatments/iui/" class="next-link">IUI Treatment →</a>
		</div>
	</section>
</Layout>

